questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a `RuntimeException` is thrown during a database operation, but the transaction is not rolling back as expected. You find the following code snippet in a `@Service` class:

java
@Service
public class InventoryService {
    public void updateStock(String itemId, int quantity) {
        try {
            executeStockUpdate(itemId, quantity);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to update stock", e);
        }
    }

    @Transactional
    public void executeStockUpdate(String itemId, int quantity) {
        inventoryRepo.update(itemId, quantity);
        if (quantity < 0) throw new RuntimeException("Invalid quantity");
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue in a high-throughput reactive gateway using `CompletableFuture`. The system is leaking threads and eventually hanging. You observe the following pattern used for service orchestration:

java
public CompletableFuture<UserDTO> fetchUser(String id) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> userService.call(id), customExecutor)
        .thenApply(user -> {
            if (user == null) throw new UserNotFoundException();
            return enrichUser(user);
        });
}

When `UserNotFoundException` occurs, downstream consumers waiting on `join()` or `get()` block indefinitely or fail without specific error details.
